-- Japan, China, India, Malaysia, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-16T22:21:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-16/japan-china-india-malaysia-south-korea-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: The Finance Ministry is set to report data on weekly
securities transactions at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo. Chief Cabinet
Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold media briefings at 11 a.m.
and 4 p.m.  
 The yield on the 1.225 percent government bond due June
2020 was 1.235 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 91.40 per dollar at 7:20 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 China: The central bank plans to sell 5 billion yuan ($732
million) of one-year notes and 18 billion yuan of three-year
securities today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due May 2020 was 3.34
percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The yuan was
at 6.8323 per dollar.  
 India: The government will report food-inflation data for
the week ended June 5. An index measuring wholesale prices of
agriculture products, including lentils, rice and vegetables,
rose 16.74 percent in the previous week from a year earlier.  
 The yield on the 7.80 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.59
percent. The rupee was at 46.56.  
 Malaysia: The government plans to sell 100 million ringgit
($30.7 million) of 364-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.06 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2570.  
 South Korea: The Ministry of Knowledge Economy will report
tomorrow sales data for major department stores in May. Spending
at the three biggest chains climbed 8.8 percent in April from a
year earlier.  
 The yield on South Korea’s 4.5 percent bond due in March
2015 was 4.40 percent. The won was at 1,210.80.  
 Singapore: The government will report non-oil export data
for May today. Economists surveyed by Bloomberg News predict a
25.7 percent increase from a year earlier, following a 29.4
percent gain in the previous month.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.57 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3934.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 40 billion baht ($1.2
billion) of 14-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.21 percent. The baht was at 32.40.  
